th America, (also) an altered form of this. The surname <i>Candler</i> is very rare in Germany."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":74,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Chandler was born in 1475, in Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England, his father, John Chandler or Chaundeler, was 26 and his mother, Jane Gitton, was 21. He married Mary Agnes Tate in 1500, in Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died before 31 January 1551, in his hometown."},"et":{"1475–before 31 January 1551":"1475–enne 31. jaanuari 1551","1475–1551":"1475–1551","1472–1514":"1472–1514","1500–1554":"1500–1554","1450–1524":"1450–1524","1455–1514":"1455–1514","October 1500":"oktoober 1500","1450":"1450","1472":"1472","1514":"1514","1524":"1524","1500":"1500","Abt. 1524":"umbes 1524","1455":"1455","1554":"1554","1475":"1475","1551":"1551","before 31 